JNKboy98 2023-09-16 2:33 PM
No, High intensity on the 2nd chorus instead of the same drop again is the way to go. That drop is so catchy that it's better left once. Armin Van Burren said that he likes putting in hooks and certain synth lines just once in a track to give that scarcity feeling. The drop is good and only having it once will give people that repeat factor. The second time is like to much sweets when a single scoop would have been perfect. Hope this describes what I mean. (edited)

rune 2023-09-18 7:23 AM
First tip I would give you is don't bail out on trying to recreate certain parts of a song (i.e. the drums or the fluttery synth here), because then you're not really learning as much
7:24 AM
Like say you get that fluttery synth down - now you know how LFOs work and what a cutoff frequency is so now you can apply it to your own songs
7:24 AM
That sort of thing
7:25 AM
Oh and don't forget to make original music from time to time. Absolutely go ahead and recreate some songs, that's how I learned alot of tricks, but you need to try and make a few new ones even if they suck
7:26 AM
A channel I'd recommend is In The Mix, he is focused generally around FL
7:27 AM
Good luck on your journey

Henry 2023-10-17 11:32 PM
This is literally my specific area of audio engineering expertise lol
11:38 PM
So... 'Spleeter' was the first AI separation, to my knowledge, and it's been around since about 2020. In 2021/2022 the concept absolutely exploded and we saw lalal.ai, demucs, UVR5, etc. Big advances and definitely approaching the top of the curve Before that, the main technique, sometimes known as "center-channel removing/isolating" (which is a deceptive term) was the best way. This is essentially what Audacity uses but I'll get more into that in a moment. This method inverts one channel of stereo, and mixes the two, so that the vocals, which are usually panned center, are cancelled out, and most everything else that isn't panned to the center, is left behind. Now that you have this mono track without vocals, you can reverse the process to obtain only the center (vocals mostly) then these vocals can be subtracted from the original stereo to have a stereo instrumental. Now the issues with this are obviously that vocals aren't always centered, and if they are, there's often stereo-reverb meaning that even if the main dry vocal is removed, remnants of it will remain. Another issue is compression in production, 'making room' in the instrumental for the vocals, and removing the vocals will leave holes and distortion. But overall, that's the idea. This technique has actually been around for more than half a century, I know a guy who did it with physical speakers back in the 70s. Audacity, and other older services, take it a step further by narrowing the vocals down to the typical frequency bands for singing, cutting off the low and high ends so as to leave behind any centered bassy parts when subtracting the vocals from the original instrumental Last thing - before spleeter there were a few other learning techniques, such as training Audition on raw vocals and using that sample to roughly remove them from the track, and also the classic spectogram 'healing tool'.
11:41 PM
